Ceteris Paribus explenations for white wine quality dataset¶

About the dataset¶

Wine quality dataset, available at: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/wine+quality connects a quality score of wine (1-10) with 11 continous attributes of its physiochemical properties:

  • fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity
  • citric acid
  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • free sulfur dioxide
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • density
  • pH
  • sulphates
  • alcohol

It contains data on both: red and white wine. I assume that quality predictors would be different for either, so I've arbitraily decided to focus on the white wine.

Used regressors¶

The prediction of wine quality can be interpreted as both: classification and regression task. I chose to treat it as the latter.

As a main regressor I chose Random Forest Regressor implemented in the scikit learn package.

As a regressor used for the sake of comparision I chose SVR implemented as well in the scikit learn package

Exemplary local model decompositions¶

Selected instances¶

I've selected three instances to make local model decompositions:

  1. A strong wine (one of the strongest alcohol percentage in the test set)

    • alcohol = 14.000 (+3.686)
    • sulphates = 0.830 (-0.089)
    • pH = 3.210 (+0.068)
    • density = 0.987 (-0.006)
    • total sulfur dioxide = 106.000 (-25.361)
    • free sulfur dioxide = 33.000 (-4.308)
    • chlorides = 0.036 (-0.009)
    • residual sugar = 1.900 (-4.791)
    • citric acid = 0.180 (-0.054)
    • volatile acidity = 0.455 (+0.072)
    • fixed acidity = 4.700 (-0.455)

  2. A sweet wine (the highest value of residual sugar in the test set)

    • alcohol = 11.700 (+1.185)
    • sulphates = 0.690 (+0.200)
    • pH = 3.390 (+0.202)
    • density = 1.039 (+0.045)
    • total sulfur dioxide = 160.000 (+21.639)
    • free sulfur dioxide = 8.000 (-27.308)
    • chlorides = 0.074 (+0.028)
    • residual sugar = 65.800 (+59.409)
    • citric acid = 0.600 (+0.266)
    • volatile acidity = 0.965 (+0.687)
    • fixed_acidity = 7.800 (+0.945)

  3. The best wine (one of the highest quality score in the test dataset)

    • alcohol = 12.500 (+1.986)
    • sulphates = 0.480 (-0.010)
    • pH = 3.280 (+0.092)
    • density = 0.990 (-0.003)
    • total sulfur dioxide = 139.000 (+0.639)
    • free sulfur dioxide = 27.000 (-8.308)
    • chlorides = 0.031 (-0.015)
    • residual sugar = 2.000 (-4.391)
    • citric acid = 0.360 (+0.026)
    • volatile acidity = 0.240 (-0.038)
    • fixed acidity = 7.400 (+0.545)

The values in the parenthasis are the difference between the local attributes values and the mean values of the attributes in the dataset.

Predictions¶

The strong got a score of 6.26, the original score was 7

The sweet wine got a score of 4.64, the original score was 6

The best wine got a score of 6.54, the original score was 8

Model decompositions¶

Strong Wine¶

Having worked on this data through past few homeworks I observed, that each model I've trained tended to corralate good quality with alcohol. Thus it was quite surprising to find out, that for the strong wine, any alcohol over 12 did not improve the score. Not-so-surprisingly lower level of alcohol reduced the final score.

Those quite clear areas of improvement can as well be seen in residual sugar and pH. Not-so-clearly in volatile acidity

Sweet Wine¶

Sweet wine seemed to be (in the model's eyes) wight below the free sulfur dioxide value that is considered to belong to average-good wine. Changing it just a little bit would acctually result in a near-perfect prediction.

Against expectation and comparison to the strong wine, alcohol in case of the sweet wine has close-to-none influence.

To further point out locallity of the explanations, the influence of pH is exactly opposite for strong and sweet wine

Best wine¶

Quite opposite to the sweet wine response, the best wine seems to have very similiar explanations to the strong wine. Those can occure, proving it is important to check for quite a few explanations before assuming close-to-global dependencies.

Inter model comparisions¶

By the nature of the regressor, every profile of SVR was much smoother than that of RF. Having said that in most cases the shape of the line was quite similiar, with slight changes in y-shift. The most standing out difference was this of the total sulfur dioxide in the strong wine. While RF profile was quite linear, with slight dent around the actual value, the SVR profile was a curve, with the highest point nearny the actual value.

This is especially interesting given that both models made very close score-wise predictions, but the explanations are quite different.

This proves that ceteris paribus profile shouldn't be used to conclude dependencies as real-world factual, but rather should only be used to describe specific model.
